      "content": "Certainly, there may be a connection. The linguistic differences could suggest a divergence in education, with the second group potentially having a higher level of education which affords them the vocabulary and confidence to frame the issue in pro-development terms. Cultural backgrounds, too, might influence the first group to communicate more emotionally to emphasize the personal stake and prevalence of community ties. The first group's resistance might indeed stem from a reduced capacity to comprehend or willingly engage with the technicalities of zoning laws, while the second group's position could reflect a more systematic view, informed by an ability to analyze and strategize future outcomes. This illustrative dichotomy in expression and engagement could bear out broader disparities in social and economic capital among the different groups—namely, that the less affected community may rely on emotion to assert their position due to lack of direct experience or stake with the proposed development, while the more affluent group, whose interests are clearly served by such developments, resort to a calculated articulation of their stance.",
